{"key":"post-16137701","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>16137701</id>\n<content>No, you replace the gauge.&amp;nbsp; Don't try to seal or otherwise repair it, unless it's leaking from where it's threaded into the lid.&amp;nbsp; In that case, tighten it up by half a turn or so.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You're supposed to let steam vent for five to ten minutes before putting the weight on or otherwise closing a valve so pressure can build.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;When your jars will lose moisture is excessive rattling or venting of steam once pressure is reached.&amp;nbsp; This is why I recommend reducing the stove to a setting that will maintain around 14 psi, once pressure is reached and steam vents a few additional times.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Your wbs is supposed to look dry after pressure cooking.&amp;nbsp; If there was visible water on the grains, they wouldn't colonize properly.&amp;nbsp; It sounds like you got the moisture content right.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>16137734</next>\n<prev>16137672</prev>\n<first>16137585</first>\n<last>16137769</last>\n<when>1335376594</when>\n<utime>04/25/12 08:56 PM</utime>\n</post>"}